# Scatter Plot


# Scatter Plot

Use scatter plots for exploring relationships between two continuous variables.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.scatter(df, x='column_x', y='column_y', color='category',
                 title='Scatter Plot Title')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Use color for categorical dimensions
- Use size for additional numeric dimension
- Add trendlines with trendline='ols'
- Consider marginal plots for distributions

# Line Chart


# Line Chart

Line charts show trends over time or continuous data.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.line(df, x='date', y='value', color='category',
              title='Line Chart Title')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Ensure x-axis is sorted chronologically
- Use markers for sparse data points
- Consider smoothing for noisy data
- Use facets for comparing multiple series

# Bar Chart


# Bar Chart

Bar charts compare categorical data.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.bar(df, x='category', y='value', color='subcategory',
             title='Bar Chart Title')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Sort bars by value for easier comparison
- Use horizontal bars for long category names
- Consider grouped or stacked bars for subcategories
- Add data labels for precise values

# Histogram


# Histogram

Histograms show the distribution of a single variable.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.histogram(df, x='value', nbins=30, color='category',
                   title='Histogram Title')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Experiment with bin count (nbins)
- Use marginal='box' or 'rug' for additional context
- Consider cumulative=True for cumulative distribution
- Overlay density curve if needed

# Box Plot


# Box Plot

Box plots show distribution statistics and outliers.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.box(df, x='category', y='value', color='category',
             title='Box Plot Title')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Use points='all' to show all data points
- Consider violin plots for density information
- Use notched=True to show confidence intervals
- Group by categories for comparison

# Heatmap


# Heatmap

Heatmaps show data in a 2D matrix with color encoding.

## Basic Example
```python
import plotly.express as px
fig = px.imshow(correlation_matrix, text_auto=True,
                title='Heatmap Title', color_continuous_scale='RdBu_r')
fig.show()
```

## Best Practices
- Choose appropriate color scale (sequential vs diverging)
- Add text annotations for readability
- Use symmetric scale for correlation matrices
- Consider aspect ratio for readability
